NAME key

DLG 0
The tea has gone cold. I spent too much time packing, or maybe I was just waiting for someone to call.
NAME cat dialog

DLG 4
I look different in this light. I wonder if the cameras in the New Country will even recognize me as the same person.
NAME item 3 dialog

DLG 7

NAME exit dialog 1

DLG 9
My whole family is in this photograph.{p}We took it in the summer before everything changed. Before I got the visa. Before the decision was made.{p}Everyone is laughing at something. I cannot remember what. I almost left the photograph. The suitcase is full now. Should I take it with me? Or should I start over? New country. New memories. New photographs?
NAME Photograph dialog

DLG a
The last diary-entry is dated the day I got my visa. After that — nothing. Like I stopped being someone who had thoughts worth keeping.
NAME Diary dialog

DLG b
Assistant Manager. That is who I was here. Over there I am just documents. Just papers proving I exist.
NAME ID dialog

DLG e
"""
You notice an old man. He has been sitting here for two hours. His flight was called twenty minutes ago. He has not moved.{p}

His eyes rest on the departures board, but they do not follow the lines. They linger somewhere beyond it, as if he is looking at something only he can see.{p}

Time passes. Announcements come and go. People leave. He stays.{p}

After a while, he speaks. The words are not meant for anyone.{p}

"I came here to leave. I think I just needed to sit with it first."{p}

The sentence fades as soon as it is spoken, as if it was never meant to be heard.{p}

He does not look around. He does not check if anyone is listening. The moment remains entirely his.{p}

You cannot but think about everything you did not sit with. Everything you rushed past to get to this gate.{p}

But now, you are waiting for your flight and there is time.{p}

Think.{p}

Was leaving always part of your plan?{p}
When did you know you were going to leave?{p}
Is there anything you regret, anything you wish you had done differently?
"""
NAME old man dialog

DLG f
"""
She is fixing his collar. He is 30 maybe. She smooths it once. Twice. Three times. You watch. You cannot stop.

{p}Her hands - Nobody will fix your collar where you are going.

{p}His face - Did you hug your mother long enough.

{p}You look away - You did this for yourself. That is allowed.
"""
NAME mother dialog

DLG g
"""
You see an old woman sitting with a young man. The old woman is fixing the collar of the young man. He seems to be in 30s. She smooths it once. Twice. Three times. You watch. You cannot stop looking..
{p}Her hands, 
{p}His face. 

{p}You cannot but ask yourself, did you hug your mother long enough before leaving?

{p}How are you feeling now? Sad? Overwhelmed?
"""
NAME mother dialog 1

DLG h
"""
You see an old woman sitting with a young man. The old woman is fixing the collar of the young man. He seems to be in 30s. She smooths it once. Twice. Three times. You watch. You cannot stop looking..
{p}Her hands, 
{p}His face. {p}Ask yourself, did you hug your mother long enough before leaving?

{p}How are you feeling now? Sad? Overwhelmed?
"""
NAME son dialog

DLG i
You notice a middle-aged woman and she is sitting in the back. {p}She seems to be crying. {p}She is not crying loudly. She is crying carefully. Like she has had practice. {p}You know that kind of crying. You have done it in bathrooms, in cars, in places where people were not supposed to see you crying. {p}She wipes her face quickly, straightens up, looks at her phone. {p}She catches your eye for one second. You both look away before you mean to. You both understand everything.
NAME sprite k dialog

DLG k
You have arrived!!!! You are looking out of the airport now.{p}The air is different. You cannot explain how. It just is.{p}The light falls differently here. The sounds are almost familiar but not quite.{p}You stand still for a moment. Just to feel it. A new country is waiting for you outside.The life you chose is waiting for you outside. 
NAME sprite l dialog

DLG n
The end
NAME ending 1

DLG o
You sit. Just to feel it.{p}Everything you left is still real. The tea. The photograph. The people at the gate.{p}They are just very far away now.{p}You pick up your bag.{p}You take one step.{p}Then another.{p}That is how it starts: THE CHOSEN LIFE of yours. 
NAME Bench dialog

DLG p
My father gave me this the day I got my visa.{p}He did not say much. He just pressed it into my hand.{p}Keep it. That is all he said.{p}I think he meant — I can always come back.{p}I think he also meant — he knows I won't.{p}Anyway, I am taking it with me. I do not know why, but I want to.
NAME key dialog

DLG q
"""
The departure gate that will take you somewhere new.{p}

But it is not time yet.{p}

You take a seat.{p}

People around you are waiting to leave too.{p} You see them.

Each of them is carrying something different.
Each of them is in a moment that is entirely their own.
"""
NAME sprite r dialog

DLG r
Step through...
NAME door 1 dialog

DLG s
<Previous room
NAME sprite u dialog

DLG t
Next>>
NAME door 21 dialog

DLG u
Next>>
NAME door 24 dialog

DLG v
Departure Gate
NAME door4 dialog

DLG w
A new country is waiting for you...outside!
NAME final door dialog

DLG x
Go back to your last night.
NAME sprite z dialog

